SURVIVORS DEVASTATED BY FIND
The remains of 215 children have been discovered on the grounds of a former Indigenous school in the Canadian city of Kamloops in British Columbia.
The Kamloops Indian Residential… More School was established in the late 19th century, with children forcibly enrolled. Residential schools were typically operated by Christian churches on behalf of the government.
A report by the Truth and Reconciliation Commission previously found more than 3,200 Indigenous students had died amid abusive treatment across the institutions, including at the Kamloops school.
Canada's Prime Minister Justin Trudeau has called the new discovery a "painful reminder of that dark and shameful chapter of our country's history".
It is believed the deaths went undocumented, however archivists are now searching for records.

SURVIVORS DEVASTATED BY FIND

The Kamloops Indian Residential School was established in the late 19th century, with children forcibly enrolled. Residential schools were typically operated by Christian churches on behalf of the government.

A report by the Truth and Reconciliation Commission previously found more than 3,200 Indigenous students had died amid abusive treatment across the institutions, including at the Kamloops school.

Canada's Prime Minister Justin Trudeau has called the new discovery a "painful reminder of that dark and shameful chapter of our country's history".

It is believed the deaths went undocumented, however archivists are now searching for records.
